After the Free International Order
CAMBRIDGE – Many analysts view the free international order as having ended with China’s rise and US President Donald Trump’s election.
But should Joe Biden, if he defeats Trump in November’s election, try to revive it?
Might the result instead be different, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are correct to point out that the American order after 1945 was neither truly global nor always very free.
It excludes more than half the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian countries.
American hegemony is always overstated.
Nevertheless, the strongest country must lead in creating global public goods, or they will not be provided – and Americans will suffer for it.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal for the Biden administration should be to build an international system based on rules with different member states participating in different issues.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
Both countries were unable to balance against American power during the 1990s and the 21st century, while the United States was fixated on pursuing freedom values at the expense of sovereignty.
The US bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the authorization of the UN Security Council.
It also supported a "Responsibility to Protect" resolution adopted by the UN General Assembly in 2005, aimed at protecting citizens who are subject to cruel treatment by their own governments – and then used this principle in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect Benghazi citizens.
Critics describe this record as American hubris in the post-Cold War era – for example, when Russia and China felt deceived by the NATO-led intervention in Libya that ultimately resulted in regime change – while defenders describe it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Nevertheless, the growth of Chinese and Russian power more strictly limits the scope for liberal interventionism.
So, what remains?
Russia and China stress the sovereign principles enshrined in the UN Charter, which stipulate that states can only wage war in self-defense or with Security Council approval.
The situation of military occupation of neighboring territories has been rare since 1945, and when it does occur, it comes at a high cost in terms of sanctions (as in Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council frequently authorizes peacekeeping forces to be deployed in troubled states, while political cooperation has also successfully curtailed the spread of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of order based on rules remains crucial.
Specifically for economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model that distorted the functions of the WTO.
The result will lead to decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is at stake.
While China complains about the US blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the US position aligns with sovereignty requirements.
After all, China has prevented Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating within its borders for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent disengagement from escalating.
Meanwhile, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
On the contrary, mutual dependence in the ecological domain creates insurmountable barriers in the face of sovereignty because threats cross borders.
Regardless of how economic globalization is set back, environmental globalization will continue, as it follows biological and physical laws that contemporary geoeconomic logic cannot affect.
The above problems threaten everyone, but no country has the ability to solve them on its own.
In issues like the COVID-19 pandemic in 2019 and climate change, power also has so-called positive-sum dimensions.
Given this premise, merely thinking about exercising power over others is not enough.
We must also reflect on exercising power together with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization benefit us and everyone.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this has not hindered cooperation between China and the United States.
Biden’s challenge is whether the US and China can cooperate to produce global public goods while competing in traditional great power domains.
The internet is a new and important issue – because it partly has a transnational nature but is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Free speech and privacy rules for the internet can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As recommended by the Global Commission on the Stability of the Internet Economy, if authoritarians also wish to achieve connectivity, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the basic structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
But when they use proxies to wage information warfare or interfere in elections (which is a violation of sovereignty), it must be met with norms such as those negotiated during the Cold War to limit escalations of maritime incidents (even though ideological hostility still exists).
The US and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and build the necessary deterrence.
Maintaining the free values of cyberspace does not mean that the US unilaterally disarms itself.
Instead, the US should distinguish between the soft power of open persuasion that can be allowed and the hard power of covert information warfare that it must respond to when initiated by others.
It can allow Russia and China to broadcast programs openly, but covert unified actions such as manipulating social media are not allowed.
Furthermore, the US will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Polling shows that the American public wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to exit alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values these principles.
If Biden wins, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the free international order.
The question is whether the United States can work with core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while also cooperating with a broader range of countries to manage rule-based international institutions required to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
